– 2 –
1 (1) Includes a comprehensive science, technology,
2 engineering and mathematics school garden program. Such a
3 program must include, without limitation, a science, technology,
4 engineering and mathematics curriculum for outdoor or hydroponic
5 gardens for pupils in kindergarten through grade 12 that is tailored
6 to pupils of the appropriate grade levels at the school;
7 (2) Is written specifically for Nevada and the desert
8 environment of Nevada;
9 (3) Complies with the standards of content and performance
10 for a course of study in science adopted by the State Board of
11 Education pursuant to NRS 389.520;
12 (4) Uses experiential learning or project-based learning to
13 teach science, technology, engineering, arts and mathematics;
14 (5) Is designed with the assistance of teachers and other
15 educational personnel with experience at the appropriate grade
16 levels at the school; and
17 (6) Involves supervised learning experiences for the pupils at
18 the school in a classroom and a school garden.
19 (c) Provide the school with assistance from members of the
20 community, including, without limitation, trained educators, local
21 farmers and local chefs.
22 (d) Provide pupils with the:
23 (1) Ability to operate a farmer’s market to sell the produce
24 from the school garden; and
25 (2) Opportunity to have a local chef or employee of a school
26 who works in food services demonstrate how to cook a meal using
27 the produce grown from the school garden.
28 (e) Establish garden teams comprised of teachers and, if such
29 persons are available, parents and members of the community. Each
30 garden team shall meet at least once each month.
31 (f) Require any local nonprofit or community-based
32 organization which will provide services to implement the program
33 for a school garden to have at least 2 years of experience
34 implementing such a program.
35 4. Money allocated pursuant to subsection 2 may be used to:
36 (a) Provide professional development for teachers regarding the:
37 (1) Use of a school garden to teach pupils with disabilities,
38 including, without limitation, training for teaching such pupils
39 science, technology, engineering and mathematics curriculum and
40 vocational training to create a career path in horticulture;
41 (2) Development and implementation of science, technology,
42 engineering, arts and mathematics curricula that incorporate the use
43 of a school garden;
44 (3) Development and implementation of training that may be
45 provided to a group or individually to teachers in how to establish
-
